---
import { icons } from "feather-icons";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import aboutImage from "../assets/images/about.jpg";
---

<section class="p-4 lg:p-10">
	<h3
		class="text-dracula-cyan my-2 flex items-center justify-center gap-x-2 text-2xl font-extrabold lg:items-end lg:text-4xl lg:leading-none"
	>
		About
		<Fragment set:html={icons.info?.toSvg({ class: "text-dracula-light w-6 h-6 lg:w-9 lg:h-9" })} />
	</h3>
	<hr
		class="bg-dracula-red from-yellow to-dracula-pink m-auto mb-4 h-2 w-1/2 rounded-lg border-none bg-gradient-to-br"
	/>
	<article class="flex flex-col items-center text-justify sm:p-4 lg:p-7 xl:px-11">
		<p class="m-auto lg:w-3/4">
			JavaScript is everywhere. In the old days, being a JavaScript developer meant that you were a front end web
			developer. Forever bound to the browser.
		</p>
		<strong class="my-8 block text-center uppercase">Those days are gone</strong>
		<p class="m-auto lg:w-3/4">
			The rise of Node.js ushered in a new era. An era where being a JavaScript developer doesnâ€™t necessarily mean
			a front-end web developer. As a JavaScript developer today, you can target more platforms than any other
			high level language.
		</p>
		<figure>
			<Image
				alt="My face"
				src={aboutImage}
				width={300}
				height={300}
				quality={75}
				class="border-dracula-blue mt-12 mb-10 h-40 w-40 rounded-full border-4 md:mb-3 lg:mb-0"
			/>
		</figure>
	</article>
</section>
